---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const banks = [
  {
    theme: 'Kingship',
    rows: [
      { q: '&lsquo;There&rsquo;s no art to find the mind&rsquo;s construction in the face&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 4 &middot; Duncan', m: 'Antithesis; dramatic irony', note: 'Duncan&rsquo;s faith that faces cannot be read is spoken just before he trusts Macbeth: the play&rsquo;s warning that good kingship and fatal naivety can be the same thing.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;More is thy due than more than all can pay&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 4 &middot; Duncan', m: 'Hyperbole', note: 'The ideal king rewards loyalty openly; the line sets a standard of gracious rule against which Macbeth&rsquo;s later reign of fear is measured.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Signs of nobleness, like stars, shall shine on all deservers&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 4 &middot; Duncan', m: 'Simile', note: 'Duncan ties good rule to natural light and order; when Macbeth begs the stars to hide their fires, the same image is turned inside out.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;The king-becoming graces&rsquo;', where: 'Act 4, Scene 3 &middot; Malcolm', m: 'Listing', note: 'Malcolm&rsquo;s catalogue of virtues defines legitimate kingship by everything Macbeth lacks, turning a character test into a political manifesto.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;This tyrant, whose sole name blisters our tongues&rsquo;', where: 'Act 4, Scene 3 &middot; Malcolm', m: 'Metaphor', note: '&lsquo;Tyrant&rsquo; replaces &lsquo;king&rsquo;: the word itself wounds, marking how far Macbeth has fallen from the sacred title he seized.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Upon my head they placed a fruitless crown&rsquo;', where: 'Act 3, Scene 1 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Metaphor', note: 'The crown he killed for is barren; he rules but founds no line, so kingship becomes a possession that gives him nothing to keep.' },
    ],
  },
  {
    theme: 'The presentation of women',
    rows: [
      { q: '&lsquo;Unsex me here&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 5 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Imperative', note: 'She asks to be emptied of womanhood to do the deed, exposing the play&rsquo;s assumption that cruelty is male and tenderness female.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Come to my woman&rsquo;s breasts, and take my milk for gall&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 5 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Grotesque imagery', note: 'Nourishment is rewritten as poison: motherhood, the age&rsquo;s emblem of the good woman, is offered up to be perverted.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;That no compunctious visitings of nature shake my fell purpose&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 5 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Personification', note: 'She treats conscience as an intruder to be barred, dramatising the effort it takes to unmake a woman&rsquo;s expected nature.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;The milk of human kindness&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 5 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Metaphor', note: 'She diagnoses her husband&rsquo;s gentleness as weakness; the nurturing image she scorns is the very quality the play proves he needed.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;I have given suck, and know how tender &rsquo;tis to love the babe that milks me&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 7 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Shocking anecdote', note: 'She invokes motherhood only to threaten its destruction, using the most female of experiences to prove she is harder than a man.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;More needs she the divine than the physician&rsquo;', where: 'Act 5, Scene 1 &middot; Doctor', m: 'Antithesis', note: 'Her sickness is named as spiritual, not medical: the woman who dismissed conscience is destroyed by it, and moral order reasserts itself.' },
    ],
  },
  {
    theme: 'Masculinity',
    rows: [
      { q: '&lsquo;I dare do all that may become a man&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 7 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Antithesis', note: 'Macbeth defines manhood as knowing where to stop; the play then tests whether that restraint or his wife&rsquo;s idea of daring is the true measure of a man.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;When you durst do it, then you were a man&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 7 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Emotional blackmail', note: 'She reduces manhood to the willingness to kill, weaponising gender to push him over the edge his conscience refused.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Was the hope drunk&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 7 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Rhetorical question', note: 'She mocks his hesitation as cowardice, staging the pressure that runs through the play: that to be a man is to act, whatever the act.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Dispute it like a man&rsquo;', where: 'Act 4, Scene 3 &middot; Malcolm', m: 'Imperative', note: 'Malcolm reaches for the same equation of manhood with action that ruined Macbeth, and Macduff&rsquo;s reply corrects it.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;I shall do so, but I must also feel it as a man&rsquo;', where: 'Act 4, Scene 3 &middot; Macduff', m: 'Antithesis', note: 'Macduff redefines masculinity to include grief: the play&rsquo;s answer to Lady Macbeth, that a man who cannot feel is not more of a man but less.' },
    ],
  },
  {
    theme: 'The supernatural and equivocation',
    rows: [
      { q: '&lsquo;Fair is foul, and foul is fair&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 1 &middot; The Witches', m: 'Chiasmus; paradox', note: 'The moral compass is spun on the first page: a world where opposites collapse, preparing every later deception and double meaning.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Instruments of darkness tell us truths&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 3 &middot; Banquo', m: 'Paradox', note: 'Banquo grasps the trap Macbeth misses: evil speaks true in order to damn, the exact equivocation England was trying in 1606.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;By the pricking of my thumbs, something wicked this way comes&rsquo;', where: 'Act 4, Scene 1 &middot; Second Witch', m: 'Rhyme; foreshadowing', note: 'The witches feel Macbeth approach as a physical wrongness; &lsquo;wicked&rsquo; now names the man himself, marking how far he has crossed into their world.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;None of woman born&rsquo;', where: 'Act 4, Scene 1 &middot; Apparition', m: 'Equivocation', note: 'A promise that sounds like safety and hides a loophole; the phrase lulls Macbeth into the recklessness that kills him.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Great Birnam wood to high Dunsinane hill&rsquo;', where: 'Act 4, Scene 1 &middot; Apparition', m: 'Equivocation; dramatic irony', note: 'An impossibility that comes true when the army carries branches: the truth was honest and murderous at once, demonology as the age believed it.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Lies like truth&rsquo;', where: 'Act 5, Scene 5 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Oxymoron', note: 'Too late, Macbeth names the method that trapped him; the whole play&rsquo;s equivocation is compressed into two words as the promises unravel.' },
    ],
  },
  {
    theme: 'Ambition',
    rows: [
      { q: '&lsquo;If chance will have me king, why, chance may crown me&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 3 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Aside', note: 'The first flicker of the wish; he hands the choice to fate to avoid owning the ambition already stirring in him.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Stars, hide your fires&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 4 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Apostrophe', note: 'He asks the heavens to look away from his desire, admitting the ambition is shameful even as he refuses to give it up.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Vaulting ambition, which o&rsquo;erleaps itself&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 7 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Metaphor', note: 'Ambition is a rider who jumps too hard and falls: Macbeth names his own fatal flaw in the very soliloquy where he decides to indulge it.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;The Prince of Cumberland&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 4 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Aside', note: 'The naming of Duncan&rsquo;s heir turns a vague wish into a rival to be removed; ambition acquires an obstacle and hardens into a plan.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;To be thus is nothing, but to be safely thus&rsquo;', where: 'Act 3, Scene 1 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Antithesis', note: 'The crown gained is already not enough: ambition, once fed, only grows more anxious, driving the second murder before the first is cold.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Cabined, cribbed, confined&rsquo;', where: 'Act 3, Scene 4 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Tricolon; plosives', note: 'The king who wanted everything now feels trapped: the hammering consonants enact a man boxed in by the very power he killed to hold.' },
    ],
  },
  {
    theme: 'Guilt and blood',
    rows: [
      { q: '&lsquo;Macbeth does murder sleep&rsquo;', where: 'Act 2, Scene 2 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Personification', note: 'The crime kills rest itself: guilt is built into the act, so Macbeth condemns himself to sleeplessness in the moment of triumph.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Will all great Neptune&rsquo;s ocean wash this blood clean from my hand&rsquo;', where: 'Act 2, Scene 2 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Hyperbole; rhetorical question', note: 'The blood is a stain the sea cannot lift: guilt is imagined as indelible, and the question already knows its answer is no.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;A little water clears us of this deed&rsquo;', where: 'Act 2, Scene 2 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Dramatic irony', note: 'Her brisk confidence is set against his despair; the water she trusts will become the spot she cannot wash away.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Blood will have blood&rsquo;', where: 'Act 3, Scene 4 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Proverb; repetition', note: 'Murder breeds murder as a law of nature: guilt hardens into a logic that drives Macbeth from one killing to the next.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;I am in blood stepped in so far&rsquo;', where: 'Act 3, Scene 4 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Metaphor', note: 'He pictures himself wading in gore, too deep to turn back; guilt becomes an excuse to go on, the point of no return spoken aloud.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Out, damned spot&rsquo;', where: 'Act 5, Scene 1 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Imperative; symbol', note: 'The confident woman is undone by a stain only she can see: guilt returns as compulsion, and her earlier &lsquo;little water&rsquo; is answered in full.' },
    ],
  },
  {
    theme: 'Appearance and reality',
    rows: [
      { q: '&lsquo;False face must hide what the false heart doth know&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 7 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Antithesis; rhyme', note: 'Macbeth adopts deceit as policy; the neat rhyme makes hypocrisy sound like wisdom, the trap the play keeps setting for those who watch faces.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Look like the time&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 5 &middot; Lady Macbeth', m: 'Imperative', note: 'She coaches her husband in performance: survival at court depends on acting a part, so appearance is treated as a skill to be managed.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;There&rsquo;s daggers in men&rsquo;s smiles&rsquo;', where: 'Act 2, Scene 3 &middot; Donalbain', m: 'Metaphor', note: 'The one clear reading in a room of pretence: a smile can be a weapon, so the sons flee a court where nothing shown can be trusted.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Is this a dagger which I see before me&rsquo;', where: 'Act 2, Scene 1 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Soliloquy; rhetorical question', note: 'The vision blurs the seen and the imagined; the audience alone shares his hallucination, so form itself stages appearance collapsing into reality.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Nothing is but what is not&rsquo;', where: 'Act 1, Scene 3 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Paradox', note: 'Reality dissolves the instant the prophecy lands: only the imagined future feels solid, and Macbeth is already living inside a fantasy of the crown.' },
    ],
  },
  {
    theme: 'Order and disorder',
    rows: [
      { q: '&lsquo;Confusion now hath made his masterpiece&rsquo;', where: 'Act 2, Scene 3 &middot; Macduff', m: 'Personification', note: 'The murder of the king is disorder&rsquo;s finest work: regicide is staged as the summit of chaos, an offence against the whole ordered world.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;The night has been unruly&rsquo;', where: 'Act 2, Scene 3 &middot; Lennox', m: 'Pathetic fallacy', note: 'Nature convulses in answer to the crime, exactly as the age expected when the Chain of Being was broken; the storm is the universe recoiling.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;The wine of life is drawn&rsquo;', where: 'Act 2, Scene 3 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Metaphor', note: 'Mourning Duncan in the language of an emptied cask, Macbeth mouths order while embodying its ruin, so hypocrisy and real loss sound in one line.' },
      { q: '&lsquo;Tomorrow, and tomorrow, and tomorrow&rsquo;', where: 'Act 5, Scene 5 &middot; Macbeth', m: 'Repetition; metre', note: 'Time itself has gone slack and meaningless: the disorder Macbeth loosed on Scotland ends inside him, as a future drained of all purpose.' },
    ],
  },
];

const total = banks.reduce((n, b) => n + b.rows.length, 0);
---

<BaseLayout title="Quotation Bank" active="quotations" description="A bank of verified Macbeth quotations organised by focus: kingship, women, masculinity, the supernatural and equivocation, ambition, guilt and blood, appearance and reality, order and disorder, each read from method to effect.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">Short. Verified. Organised by focus.</p>
      <h1>Quotation bank</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        Evidence is not about covering the plot; it is about choosing the line that gives you the most
        to say. A short quotation you can open up on language, form and context will always beat a long
        one you can only summarise. This bank is arranged around the three set questions and the main
        themes, so you can work straight from your chosen title. Every line is checked against the play,
        but copy each one accurately from your own annotated edition before it goes in an essay.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap">
      {banks.map((bank) => (
        <div>
          <h2>{bank.theme}</h2>
          <table class="quote-table">
            <thead><tr><th>Quotation (act and scene)</th><th>Method</th><th>Why it earns its place</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              {bank.rows.map((r) => (
                <tr>
                  <td class="q"><span set:html={r.q}></span><br /><span class="small" set:html={r.where}></span></td>
                  <td class="m">{r.m}</td>
                  <td><span set:html={r.note}></span></td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      ))}

      <div class="box think" style="max-width: 46rem;">
        <h3>Does this quotation earn its place?</h3>
        <p>
          Test every line with three questions. First, can you name a method and then push it to an
          effect: if all you can write is &lsquo;this shows&rsquo;, the quotation is carrying you rather
          than the other way round. Second, does it open onto context, a word or image you can loop back
          to the Jacobean world? Third, is it short enough to quote whole and analyse closely, a phrase
          rather than a speech? A line that answers all three gives you something to argue. A line that
          only proves the plot happened does not, however famous it is.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
